{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17512633","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17512633"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:58:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:58:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11930"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11930"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.11,0.05,0.41,0.27]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4526"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50539"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4526","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4526"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11930"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35758"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"247"},{"type":"tags","id":"595"},{"type":"tags","id":"1352"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6676"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6694"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14158"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50539","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/50539"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a two week history of right breast pain and swelling. She had seen her general practitioner one week ago, who had commenced her on oral cephalexin. However, the pain has persisted and the patient is now worried that the redness has spread. She stopped breastfeeding one month ago and has type 1 diabetes mellitus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination her blood pressure is 116/72 mmHg, pulse 84/min and temperature 37.6\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. Her right breast is erythematous and tender on palpation with an area of fluctuance on the superio-medial aspect. There is no apparent discharge.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassurance and encourage to resume breastfeeding","Continue oral antibiotics and apply warm compresses","Parenteral antibiotics","Ultrasound-guided needle aspiration","Surgical incision and drainage"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIt is very likely that this patient is developing a breast abscess. The erythema, tenderness and fluctuance is highly suggestive of an abscess formation. She is not responding to oral antibiotics because of the untreated underlying abscess.  \u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound-guided needle aspiration \u003C/strong\u003Ewould be the initial step in management. This would be both diagnostic and therapeutic (drainage).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance \u003C/strong\u003Ealone\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Ewould not be appropriate due to the high likelihood of abscess formation and concern of spreading erythema. In this case, lactational mastitis has likely progressed into an abscess and prompt empirical intravenous antibiotics with drainage is recommended.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEmpirical parenteral antibiotics \u003C/strong\u003Ewould not be required unless the patient was systematically unwell. If the patient was systemically unwell, particularly as she has diabetes mellitus, then admission for intravenous antibiotics while waiting for an ultrasound and needle aspiration would then be recommended. Empirical antibiotic therapy for primary breast abscesses should include activity against Staphylococcus aureus. However, it is not a definitive treatment for a proven abscess.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgical incision and drainage\u003C/strong\u003E can be considered if the skin is thin with or without necrosis and if the abscess is not responsive to aspiration and antibiotic therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EContinuing the \u003Cstrong\u003Eoral antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E alone would not be effective due to the failed resolution of symptoms with oral therapy. The patient is not responding to oral antibiotics because of the untreated underlying abscess - drainage of the abscess with appropriate oral antibiotics and review with a repeat ultrasound examination and possible further aspiration within a week would be appropriate without the need for intravenous antibiotic therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Options for breast drainage include needle aspiration and surgical drainage and intervention is guided by clinical history and examination"],"references":["Kataria K, Srivastava A, Dhar A. Management of lactational mastitis and breast abscesses: review of current knowledge and practice. Indian J Surg. 2013 Dec;75(6):430-5. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3900741/","Dixon JM, Khan LR. Treatment of breast infection. BMJ. 2011 Feb 11;342:d396.  Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21317199/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35758"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11930"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"35758","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/35758"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-12T20:43:58+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-12T20:43:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4526"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"50539"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\u